Asian Journal of Psychiatry
journal homepage: www.elsevier.com/locate/ajp
The eﬃcacy of zinc augmentation in children with attention deﬁcit
hyperactivity disorder under treatment with methylphenidate: A
randomized controlled trial
Seyyed Gholamreza Noorazara, Ayub Malekb, Sima Mir Aghaeic, Neda Yasaminehd,
Parinaz Kalejahie,*
a Research Center of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences, Tabriz University of Medical Sciences, Tabriz, Iran
b Center of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences, Tabriz University of Medical Sciences, Tabriz, Iran
c Tabriz University of Medical Sciences, Tabriz, Iran
d Dental and Periodontal Research Center, Tabriz University of Medical Sciences, Tabriz, Iran
e Nutrition Research Center, Tabriz University of Medical Sciences, Tabriz, Iran
A R T I C L E I N F O
Keywords:
Attention deﬁcit hyperactivity disorder
Zinc
Methylphenidate
Connors questionnaire
Augmentation
A B S T R A C T
Introduction: Regarding to the role of the zinc in the metabolism of the central nervous system and the corre-
lation of zinc supplementation in the treatment of any Attention deﬁcit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) symp-
toms, this study was conducted to evaluate the complementary eﬀects of this nutrient.
Method: This was a double-blind randomized clinical trial study and 60 children with ADHD who were treated
with methylphenidate were chosen by random allocation and were divided in the two groups: 30 for the case and
30 for the control group. The treatment in case group was augmented with zinc. Duration of study was six weeks.
Result: Forty eight (80%) of participants were boy and 12 (20%) were girl. The mean age of patients was
9.6 ± 1.70 years. There was no signiﬁcant diﬀerence between the two groups after the intervention in terms of
total score, hyperactivity and impulsivity subscales during variance analysis, but there was a signiﬁcant dif-
ference between the mean of inattention score.
Conclusion: Augmentation with zinc can enhance the improvement of inattention.
1. Introduction
ADHD is one of the most common psychiatric disorder among
children and adolescent. Its core symptoms are hyperactivity/im-
pulsivity and inattention that their aﬀect learning, cognition and per-
sonal relationship (Association AP, Association AP, 2000). Failure to
identify and proper intervention can lead to irreparable complications
and injuries (Brown, 2009). The worldwide prevalence of this disorder
is estimated to be between 5% and 10% in children ages and more in
boys (Sayal et al., 2017). The exact etiology of this disorder is unknown,
but various studies have suggested that genetic factors, brain damage,
low birth weight, imbalance of neurotransmitters, heavy metal toxicity,
and nutritional deﬁciencies have an eﬀect on the incidence of this
disorder (Nigg, 2012; Sharma and Couture, 2014; Jensen, 2000).
Zinc is an essential cofactor in the metabolism of neurotransmitters,
prostaglandins, melatonin, and indirect dopamine (Hambidge and
Krebs, 2007; Schmitt and Reith, 2011). Zinc increases methylphenidate
aﬃnity to the dopamine transporter and also it has an eﬀect on cell
membrane stability, antioxidant and hormonal performance. These
have an indirect role in brain function (Toren et al., 1996). Also zinc is
important in converting pyridoxine (B6) to its active form phosphate
pyridoxal that it is essential in converting tryptophan to serotonin
(Mahmoodi and Kimiagar, 2001; Fesharakinia et al., 2009). It seems
that zinc deﬁciency can cause brain dysfunction in ADHD children
(Arnold and DiSilvestro, 2005). In some studies shows that serum and
plasma levels of Zn in ADHD children were lower than healthy control
(Arnold et al., 2011; Bekaroğlu et al., 1996).
Arnold et al. The study showed that children with ADHD has lower
Zn serum level and this decrease correlate with inattention subscale in
parent and teacher test.
In a clinical trial conducted in Turkey on children with ADHD and
using zinc sulfate as monotherapy, supplementation of 150 mg/day for
