12 weeks resulted in a signiﬁcant reduction in symptoms of hyper-
activity, impulsivity and social disturbances, but there was no eﬀect on
improving inattention symptoms (Bilici et al., 2004).The number of
studies done in this area is very limited, and on the other hand, due to
the relatively high prevalence and problems with the therapeutic
methods of this disorder, it seems that identifying eﬀective nutritional
interventions as an alternative or complementary therapies for pre-
vention and control Some of the symptoms of this disorder are a useful
step in reducing the problems of ADHD patients.
2. Method
This study was performed as a double-blind randomized clinical
trial on children with attention deﬁcit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD)
and was registered on the Iranian clinical trial site (IRCT Code:
IRCT2016050716077N5)
and
the
regional
code
of
ethics
was
TBZMED.REC.1394.1131
The inclusion criteria were:
Children aged 7–12 years, diagnosis of ADHD by a child psychiatrist
(subspecialized in children and adolescent psychiatry), no contra-
indications for zinc supplements, such as Copper deﬁciency, IQ of > 70,
no other psychiatric disorders, and conﬁrmation with K-SADS form,
non-use of zinc supplementation during the last two months, treatment
with methylphenidate tablets as a therapeutic drug at a dose of
0.5–1 mg/kg/day, inform consent by parents and oral assent from
children, and having no special diet. Exclusion criteria also include
having other major psychiatric disorders, according to K-SADS, change
in the treatment and discontinuation of drugs for any reason, including
the occurrence of drug complications and consumption of Zn in the last
two months ago. A convenience sample of 60 children aged 7–12 with
ADHD were selected with randomly allocated using Stata software and
divided in 2 groups of 30 participants. The control group (A) was
treated with 0.5–1 mg/kg/day methylphenidate plus placebo. The pla-
cebo and zinc syrups were prepared and labeled by Razak Company and
in terms of appearance were quite similar. Case group (B) was treated
with 0.5–1 mg/kg/day methylphenidate plus 10 mg Zn (10 cc zinc
sulfate syrup) and there was no diﬀerence in two groups regarding the
dose of methylphenidate. Duration of study was 6 weeks and severity of
symptoms were measured by the Connors Parent’s Questionnaire before
the intervention and after completion of the intervention. This scale is
answered by parents and has 4 sub-scales and if completed by parents,
can detect 74% of the students with ADHD and have a reliability and
validity of above 0.75 and is approved by psychiatrists. In a study
conducted in Iran by Khushabi et al. was performed on 2667 students,
Using Pearson correlation and Cronbach’s alpha, The correlation of
each question with the total test as well as the validity of the test was
evaluated (α = 0 0.93) and it was shown that this tool measured ADHD
subscales with high precision (Khushabi, 2019).
For measurement Zn intake from diet before and after intervention a
24-h recall questionnaire was completed. Finally, all of the data were
entered into SPSS version 16 and analyzed by statistical methods.
3. Result
Of the 60 children studied, 48 (80%) were boy and 12 (20%) were
girls and the mean age of the patients was 9.69 ± 1.70 years. In the
control group, 20 children (67.5%) were boy and 10 children (32.5%)
were girl in the control group (A), while in the case group (B), the
number of boys was 28 (92.5%) and the number of girls was only 2
(7.5%). The comparison of the number of boys and girls in the two
groups was statistically signiﬁcant. (p = 0.005). Also, in the mean age
of the two groups, the mean age in the control group (A) was
9.30 ± 1.38and in the case group (B) was 8.87 ± 1.97, this diﬀerence
was not statistically signiﬁcant (p = 0.26).
The mean of the total score, hyperactivity and impulsivity posi-
tionality score before intervention was compared in terms of homo-
geneity of regression slope in the two groups, which results showed
homogeneity of regressions and no signiﬁcant diﬀerence between the
two groups (p = 0.14, p = 0.79, p = 0.55) respectively. The Levene test
was used to compare the variance of the two groups. According to the
homogeneity of the variance, there was no signiﬁcant diﬀerence be-
tween the two groups (p = 0.50, p = 0.10, p = 0.50).
Comparing the two groups during the Covariance analysis, there
was no signiﬁcant diﬀerence between the mean total score, hyper-
activity and impulsivity positionality score after the removal of the
pretest eﬀect (p = 0.14, p = 0.55, p = 0.20) respectively.
The mean of inattention score before intervention was compared in
terms of homogeneity of regression slope in the two groups, which
results showed homogeneity of regressions and no signiﬁcant diﬀerence
between the two groups (p = 0.54). The Levene test was used to com-
pare the variance of the two groups. According to the homogeneity of
the variance, there was no signiﬁcant diﬀerence between the two
groups (p = 0.55).
Comparing the two groups during the Covariance analysis, there
was a signiﬁcant diﬀerence between the mean of inattention score after
the removal of the pretest eﬀect (p = 0.02) and in the case group there
was a better improvement than the control group. Data was shown in
Table 1
