psychiatric can continue until adulthood period (Barkley, 2014; Arnold
et al., 2005). Pharmacological and behavioral treatments have partial
eﬀect and cannot result in full remission (Arnold et al., 2005). There-
fore, in recent years, signiﬁcant research has been done to examine the
role of environmental factors, especially nutritional factors, on the
development of ADHD, and even the improvement and treatment of the
ADHD children (Banerjee et al., 2007). In a number of studies, zinc
augmentation or complementation has a positive role in the treatment
of ADHD patients, and they are safe and eﬀective (Arnold and
DiSilvestro, 2005; Arnold et al., 2011; Bilici et al., 2004). On the other
hand, some studies have shown that zinc augmentation can cause sig-
niﬁcant improvement in these children. In Akhondzadeh et al. study
about comparing two groups of patients with ADHD (with or without
Zn augmentation) who were treated with a conventional treatment case
group has more improvement according to parent rating (Akhondzadeh
et al., 2004). Huss et al. showed consumption of poly saturated fatty
acids (omega3, 6) with complementation of zinc and magnesium can
improve ADHD symptoms after 12 weeks in 810 children (Huss et al.,
2010). In another study by Arnold et al. on 52 children with ADHD who
they were treated with amphetamine and complementation or am-
phetamine and placebo improvement in the case and control groups not
only had not signiﬁcant diﬀerence, but also case group had 37% lower
plasma levels of conventional drugs (Arnold et al., 2011) and they re-
sulted that they cannot generalized the results of eastern studies to all
children with ADHD. In our study augmentation with zinc cannot im-
prove the ADHD total score between two groups, but improvement in
inattention subscale was better in case group by comparing to the
control, noticing that there is no signiﬁcant diﬀerence between two
groups before the intervention. But there is a signiﬁcant diﬀerence
between two groups regarding sex ratio and it may be a limitation of
the study. Another limitation was also present in this study, we used
only the Connors Parent’s Questionnaire because of the budget con-
straint. Although this scale has standardized structure to complement
the diagnostic evaluations, but accompanying teachers’ questionnaires
with parents could have diﬀerent perceptions and perspectives of the
child.
5. Conclusion
In the present study, zinc augmentation in children with Attention
deﬁcit hyperactivity disorder under treatment with methylphenidate
did not signiﬁcantly improve the total score, hyperactivity and im-
pulsivity subscales, but showed a signiﬁcant improvement in the score
of attention.
